<font color="#FF0000">MAYAGUEZ REPLY</font><br>
<tt>Wed Dec  4  1:14:29 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I have just read an account of the Mayaguez on page 155 of a new book entitled &quot;Pararescue, 50 Years, 1943-1993, A Commemorative History.&quot;  In it they name the pararescueman who were on the mission.  It states:<br><br>
   &quot;On the first assault wave, three Knives are destroyed and two are severely damaged.  The Jollies are driven off under punishing enemy fire.  Through repeated attempts, the forces are equally able to land some 222 Marines in an attempt to secure the island and recover the crew of the SS Mayaguez which has been kidnapped by the KR.<br>
   &quot;But the crew is never on the island.  Now it becomes a fight to disengage the Marines from the deeply dug-in, strongly fortified, and well-seasoned force of KRs.  All day the fighting is intense with not quarter rendered to either side.  Helicopters and men are mauled with predictable reliability, the KIA and WIA tolls mount, but the KR receive the greater punishment.  By nightfall, both sides are heavily mauled.  Finally, at nearly 2000hours the last Marines are extracted and the SAR force returns to Utapo.<br>
   &quot;Of the fifteen helicopters that saw action, four are destroyed and nine damaged.  Two hundred and thirty men are inserted, then extracted.  U.S. casualties are fifteen KIA, forty-nine WIA, and three MIA.  Of the twenty-two pararescuemen who participated in the operation, five are awarded the Silver Star for gallantry while seventeen receive the DFC or Air Medal...&quot;<br><br>
It goes on to list those who received medals.  <br><br>
From what I can tell of this narrative, it is possible that the three MIA were the three Knife aircraft pilots, but you need to check that out with those listed below.<br><br>
The book can be obtained from:  <br><br>
